    line-height: 1.6;"><p>(Imagine George Carlin's voice, his delivery filled with wit and a sharp edge of sarcasm, as he delves into the peculiar world of online opinions).</p>
<p>So folks, have you ever noticed that whenever you're scrolling through the enlightened swamps of Reddit, you stumble upon these Herculean moral debates? I mean, there are people out there on the front lines, taking a stand against Japanese-style cartoons known as "loli." Now, I don't want to get into the particulars here, because that's a rabbit hole lined with weirdness and body pillows that I'm happy to say I've never fallen into. </p>
<p>But isn't it funny—no, not "ha ha" funny, more like "my God, what a wacky species we are" funny—that a lot of the staunchly anti-loli commentary comes from accounts that have been banned? It's like they're trying to reach us from the great Reddit beyond. "Remember me? I was the guy who posted all that enlightening content about why water is too wet and why breathing is overrated. Now, I shall rise from my banishment to drop one last nugget of wisdom about your cartoon choices!"</p>
