lled. We do<br/>definitely see it in Amarapura Anthony as well and it is something we have<br/>continued to talk about as this class has progressed. We also see something<br/>to do with the role of women. And we&#x27;ll talk a little bit about this today, but<br/>we have seen this in every film that we have seen so far. So we could say it<br/>was definitely there in a car. It&#x27;s to some extent with the role of parity as<br/>mother was very present in Amar Akbar Anthony. It is definitely a theme<br/>that we will talk about for today&#x27;s film Hamade Haikan and it also emerges<br/>in the other film we saw, well, we could kind of see. That are present in<br/>people live and it&#x27;s definitely very present in Jason Toshima. Right. So, so it&#x27;s<br/>it&#x27;s something that kind of every single film in some way has contributed to<br/>these major themes. I wonder if you think or if you can think of any other<br/>themes that have emerged as we are talking about this. You also or I would<br/>like you to think also about anything else that really stands out in all of the<br/>films that could. Kind of combine them and look at them as a project, right?<br/>So we decided when we started class that Bollywood film is a text. It&#x27;s a<br/>discourse, which essentially means that it is not necessarily just what you<br/>see, but it is doing a lot more than that. When we are looking at all of these<br/>themes, we are really saying that we are not just looking at film as it as it<br/>presents itself. We are also looking at what else is it saying and a lot of our<br/>films are saying things about these things. In fact, as I&#x27;m looking at this, we<br/>could very safely say that JSON Toshima is also about nation building. We<br/>actually talked about it in terms of nation building. So with respect to all of<br/>these. We will continue to add more films to these themes. We will actually<br/>also add themes. So one of the themes that that I&#x27;ve not written down here<br